{
  "answer": "**Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 75** enumerates a woman's separate property (*strīdhana*) as six-fold.[^1]\n\nThe verse introducing the six-fold list is:  \n> What is given before the nuptial fire (*adhyagni*), what is given at the bridal procession (*adhyāvāhanika*), and what is given to a woman out of affection, and what is received from a brother, mother, or father—Woman's Property (*strīdhana*) is remembered as six-fold. // K_894 //[^2]\n\nThe verse defining *pādavandanika*—the gift made for bowing at the feet of one's mother-in-law or father-in-law—groups it with what is given out of affection (*prītidatta*):  \n> Whatever is given out of affection by a mother-in-law or a father-in-law, and what is given for bowing at their feet (*pādavandanika*), is called a gift of affection (*prītidatta*). // K_897 //[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Kātyāyana Smṛti*, [Chapter 75](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/75/translation/).\n[^2]: *Kātyāyana Smṛti*, [Chapter 75](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/75/translation/#p-b8596e).\n[^3]: *Kātyāyana Smṛti*, [Chapter 75](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/75/translation/#p-e0c275).",
